[00:01.076]Passage 58. | 第58段。
[00:03.023]A gifted American psychologist has said, worry is a spasm of the emotion. | 一位有天赋的美国心理学家说过，忧虑是情感的痉挛。
[00:08.833]The mind catches hold of something and will not let it go. | 心智抓住某物不肯放手。
[00:13.123]It is useless to argue with the mind in this condition. | 在这种情况下，与心智争辩是无用的。
[00:16.483]The stronger the will, the more futile the task. | 意志越强，任务就越徒劳。
[00:19.783]One can only gently insinuate something else into its convulsive grasp. | 人们只能轻轻地将其他事物潜入其痉挛的掌控中。
[00:24.493]And if this something else is rightly chosen, if it is really attended by the illumination of another field of interest, gradually and often quite swiftly, the old and due grip relaxes. | 如果这其他事物选择得当，如果它真的得到了另一个兴趣领域的启发，那么，渐渐地，而且往往很快地，旧有而适当的抓握就会放松。
[00:36.633]And the process of recuperation and repair begins. | 康复和修复的过程便开始了。
[00:41.403]The cultivation of a hobby and new forms of interest is therefore a policy of first importance to a public man. | 因此，培养爱好和新的兴趣形式对公众人物来说是首要的策略。
[00:48.333]But this is not a business that can be undertaken in a day, or swiftly improvised by a mere command of the will. | 但这并非一日之功，也不是仅凭意志就能迅速完成的。
[00:55.333]The growth of alternative mental interests is a long process. | 培养替代性精神兴趣是一个漫长的过程。
[01:00.313]The seeds must be carefully chosen. | 种子必须精心挑选。
[01:02.583]They must fall on good ground. | 它们必须落在肥沃的土壤上。
[01:04.493]They must be sedulously tended. | 它们必须勤勉地照料。
[01:07.413]If the vivifying fruits are to be at hand when needed. | 如果需要时要有生机勃勃的果实可供取用。
[01:11.393]To be really happy and really safe, one ought to have at least two or three hobbies, and they must all be real. | 要想真正快乐和真正安全，一个人至少应该有两三个爱好，而且它们都必须是真实的。
[01:18.063]It is no use starting late in life to say, I will take an interest in this or that. | 在生命的后期才开始说，我对这个或那个感兴趣，是没有用的。
[01:24.473]Such an attempt only aggravates the strain of mental effort. | 这样的尝试只会加剧精神努力的紧张。
[01:28.273]A man may acquire great knowledge of topics unconnected with his daily work, and yet hardly get any benefit or relief. | 一个人可能获得大量与日常工作无关的知识，但却几乎得不到任何益处或解脱。
[01:36.573]It is no use doing what you like, you have got to like what you do. | 做你喜欢的事情没有用，你必须喜欢你所做的事情。
[01:41.563]Broadly speaking, human beings may be divided into three classes. | 广义地说，人类可以分为三类。
[01:46.333]Those who are toiled to death, those who are worried to death, and those who are bored to death. | 劳累至死的人，忧虑至死的人，以及无聊至死的人。
[01:54.343]It is no use offering the manual laborer, tied out with a hard week's sweat and effort, the chance of playing a game of football or baseball on Saturday afternoon. | 让一个因一周辛勤劳动而精疲力尽的体力劳动者，在周六下午有机会踢足球或打棒球是毫无意义的。
[02:04.383]It is no use inviting the politician or the professional or businessman, who has been working or worrying about serious things for six days, to work or worry about trifling things at the weekend. | 邀请一个已经工作或为严肃事情担忧了六天的政治家、专业人士或商人，在周末再为琐事工作或担忧，是毫无意义的。
[02:16.923]As for the unfortunate people who can command everything they want, who can gratify every caprice and lay their hands on almost every object of desire, | 至于那些不幸的人，他们可以掌控一切想要的东西，可以满足每一个奇想，并几乎可以得到每一个渴望的对象，
[02:25.683]For them a new pleasure, a new excitement is only an additional satiation. | 对他们来说，新的乐趣，新的兴奋，不过是额外的满足。
[02:31.253]In vain they rush frantically round from place to place, trying to escape from avenging boredom by mere clatter and motion. | 他们徒劳地四处奔波，试图通过单纯的喧嚣和运动来逃避报复性的无聊。
[02:39.373]For them, discipline in one form or another is the most hopeful path. | 对他们来说，某种形式的纪律是最有希望的道路。
[02:45.023]It may also be said that rational, industrious, useful human beings are divided into two classes. | 也可以说，理性的、勤奋的、有用的_人_类分为两类。
[02:51.943]First, those whose work is work, and whose pleasure is pleasure. | 首先，那些工作是工作，享乐是享乐的人。
[02:56.403]And secondly, those whose work and pleasure are one. | 其次，那些工作和享乐合二为一的人。
[03:00.413]Of these the former are the majority. | 其中前者是大多数。
[03:03.043]They have their compensations. | 他们有自己的补偿。
